Q4["Neo-esophagus Creation (Gastric Pull-up)"] = [
    {"question": "What vascular pedicle supports the gastric conduit for esophageal replacement?", "answer": "The right gastroepiploic artery (from GDA/celiac trunk). All other gastric vessels are divided. The conduit's viability depends entirely on this pedicle and its intramural submucosal arcade."},
    {"question": "What are the three possible routes for the gastric conduit?", "answer": "Posterior mediastinal (orthotopic, esophageal bed -- shortest, preferred), substernal/retrosternal (if posterior mediastinum is hostile), subcutaneous (rarely, for salvage). Posterior is shortest with best conduit perfusion."},
    {"question": "What conduit width is optimal, and why?", "answer": "3-5cm wide tubular conduit along the greater curvature. Too narrow (<3cm): inadequate blood supply, stricture. Too wide (>6cm): redundancy, poor emptying, aspiration. The conduit is created with a linear stapler from the antrum to the fundus."},
    {"question": "What is conduit necrosis mortality?", "answer": "30-50% mortality. Presents with sepsis, mediastinitis, conduit breakdown. Caused by tension, twist, or right gastroepiploic insufficiency. Requires emergent takedown, cervical esophagostomy, and feeding access."},
    {"question": "Why is pyloroplasty/pyloromyotomy performed with gastric pull-up?", "answer": "Vagus nerves are divided during esophagectomy, causing pyloric spasm and conduit outlet obstruction. Pyloroplasty prevents gastric retention, aspiration, and conduit distension. Botulinum toxin injection is an alternative."}
]

